{quote}
Currently, we must specify at least one user to have access to a given branch. This ticket is a request to add a check box that says "Lock Branch," or at least take out the one-user minimum requirement.
{quote}

Allow a branch to be "locked" and prevent further operations on that branch.

*Rating*: :) Good

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
Pull requests really help with self review and a once-over code review by others
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
Remember me doesn't. It's somewhat forgetful - possibly because the remember me tokens expire when stash reboots. When I get prompted to log in, I get no hint as to what failed with the process. Thankfully the error I'd seen a month ago telling me my account may have been compromised (wtf? Via a remember me token??) is not shown this time.
{panel}

From [SSP-393|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/SSP-393]:

{quote}
In case this ever comes up again, Stash works fine on SQL Server Express as long as it's an express edition of a supported SQL Server version (2008 or 2012). stash-dev (stash-windows) is using SQL Server Express 2008 R2 for internal dogfooding.
{quote}

Please update https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Supported+platforms to include this info - thanks!

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
The code from this pull request has been merged but Stash doesn't notice.

https://stash.atlassian.com/projects/CONF/repos/confluence/pull-requests/373/diff
{panel}

eg:

{noformat} 
Using the {{ProjectResource}} as a guide, document the following REST resources:
{noformat}

This warning is all over one customer's logs:

{{c.a.c.d.DbCachingRemoteChangeOperations remote username [ hemant ] casing differs from local username [ Hemant ]. User details will be kept updated, but the username cannot be updated}}

It comes from crowd.  It'd be nice to get rid of it by ensuring our user names match crowds.

*Rating*: :D Awesome!

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
The rotating stash logo!
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
* Being able to comment based on commit diff for PR (rather than overall diff)
* See diff of file with full context
{panel}

{quote}
We're getting captcha challenges at the command line. We'd like this disabled as the feature is moot on a product behind the firewall. Please let me know how we can turn this feature off entirely.
{quote}

In repo git://git.acme.com/some/repo.git the default branch is not a master, but 'my-branch'. But it also contains 'master' branch.
{{git clone --bare git://git.acme.com/some/repo.git}}
{{cd repo}}
{{git push --mirror ssh://git@stash.acme.com:7999/SOME/repo.git}}

After this in Stash in repository 'repo' the default branch is not 'my-branch', but 'master'. It is wrong. The GitHub enterprise make this import right ;)

*Rating*: :) Good

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
Pushing stuff.
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
Got an email about a pull request update. 

It said that "Eduardo Garcia" pushes some changes, but the commits were from Ivan Loire (and pushed by him).

Seems some is a bit off there?
{panel}

!email-screenshot.jpg!

*Rating*: ;) Meh!

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
When I view a project and its list of repo's there is a fair bit of dead UI space.

{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
Can you provide me the clone URL in the form of a button I can click to dump the URL into my copy buffer.
This will save me having to click into each repo to get the repo URL when I need to clone a number of repos.
{panel}

*Rating*: :) Good

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
simple UI
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
when I go from the list of commits (after picking a particular branch) down to a commit, I cannot find a way to return to the list of commits that keeps the branch I selected.  Currently it keeps returning me to the list of commits on master.
{panel}

*Rating*: :) Good

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
Lots of things
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
I'm not sure whether or not I'm watching a pull request.

There's a big grey thing that says "watchin" on the top right. Clicking on it changes it from one shade of grey to a slightly different shade of grey. I'm not sure what these shades signify.

Other systems change wording between "watch" or "Start watching" and "watching" or "already watching" so that users can understand the current state more easily.

(If the colours were sufficiently different I could probably, after some training, use the color to tell at a glance whether I'm watching or not, so the colour would be more useful than the words. The two shades of grey don't seem easily distinguishable though, and even after I've toggled colours a few times I still can't figure out which of the two almost-identical shades has what meaning, so I can't train myself to recognise the colours)
{panel}

Stash should not output language identifiers as part of the code block when using fenced code blocks. This currently occurs for README.md files saved in Stash repos. Ideally these identifiers would specify syntax highlighting.

Example fenced block:

{code}
```js
document;
```
{code}

See: http://github.github.com/github-flavored-markdown/

These are non-standard Markdown features, however GitHub-flavored Markdown is popular enough that it should at the very least fall back gracefully rather than displaying an invalid/unintentional code snippet.
